00:08:12.920 --> 00:08:16.610
the rate of this,
I haven't measured it,

00:08:16.610 --> 00:08:20.300
but the rate would go as some
relationship involving the

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:39.400
concentration of diborane
to some power, n.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:27.710
So, we've seen that,
but now I want to do is I want to

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:31.420
ask, what is the process by which
boron enters the silicon?

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:35.140
So, now I want to zoom in here to
the near surface.

00:08:35.140 --> 00:08:38.850
And here's the free surface of
silicon. This is the surface.

00:08:38.850 --> 00:08:42.570
This is inside the wafer. And,
I've got boron that's decomposing

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:46.280
and dissolving.
Remember, it goes up

00:08:46.280 --> 00:09:05.360
substitutionally, sitting
on silicon sites.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:55.450
So, now I'm asking,
how does the boron enter the silicon?

00:08:55.450 --> 00:09:00.900
What are the kinetics of the
ingress of boron?

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:06.360
So, that's what we want to ask:
rate of ingress of boron through

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:11.810
silicon. That's what we want to
look at. And,

00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:17.270
this is not some kind of a
cooperative process because

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:22.900
the silicon is solid.
So, individual atoms have to move

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:28.720
step by step through because it's a
substitutional solution that's

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:34.540
forming here. So,
we can take a guess at it.

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:40.360
If I now make this the coordinate
system, call the free surface x

00:09:40.360 --> 00:09:46.180
equals zero, and this is moving down
