00:09:46.180 --> 00:10:03.693
I can make a plot of ingress of
boron into silicon.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
So, this is x which is depth from
surface. This is the free surface

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
at x equals zero.
And, I'm going to fix the

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
concentration of diborane in the
reactor. And so,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
the concentration of boron at the
surface will be fixed.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
As long as I keep the concentration
of diborane fixed,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
concentration of boron at the
surface will be fixed.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
So, what I'm going to do is plot
the concentration of boron in the

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
silicon as a function of
depth from the surface.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:28.130
And, we know deep inside the silicon,
there's no boron.

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:32.260
So, here it should be zero.
We know at the surface it's

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:36.390
constant. The question is,
what is the shape of the curve?

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:40.530
Just as I showed you last day, we
talked about first order,

00:10:40.530 --> 00:10:44.660
second order. What it boils down to
is, what is the shape of the curve?

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:48.790
And, we know it's going to look
something like this.

00:10:48.790 --> 00:10:52.930
Doesn't that look a lot like the
attenuation curve for the loss of

00:10:52.930 --> 00:10:57.330
matter in a chemical reaction?
It starts at some constant value and

00:10:57.330 --> 00:11:01.990
trails off asymptotically.
So, really the question is,

00:11:01.990 --> 00:11:06.660
what is the shape? And, how do we
answer that question?

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:11.330
We can't look at this and eyeball
it. Instead, what we do is we do a

00:11:11.330 --> 00:11:15.990
new mapping. Map concentration into
