And away we go. 1855: so,
what did he tell us in this

00:13:12.190 --> 00:13:16.460
important paper?
Well, let's take a look at his

00:13:16.460 --> 00:13:20.730
representation of what's going on in
this process. He was able to

00:13:20.730 --> 00:13:40.726
quantify this and give us a measure
that has predictive capacity.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:11.000
And what he said was that the rate
of ingress expressed by a term

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:17.000
called flux, flux measures the rate
of infusion. It's a mass flow rate.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:23.000
So, clearly it must have some kind
of units of mass per unit time,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:29.000
so I'm going to use SI units,
kilograms per second,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:35.000
but diffusion is quantified on the
basis of unit cross sectional area.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:14:00.830
So it's a mass flow rate of species,
i, in, I'm going to make it in one

00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:06.660
direction, in the x direction,
the way I've set things up in a

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:12.490
previous sketch.
So, it's kilograms per second on a

00:14:12.490 --> 00:14:18.330
unit area a basis.
So, flux is mass flow rate per unit

00:14:18.330 --> 00:14:24.160
area. So, the flux of species i,
what he observed is it's related to

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:40.920
the concentration gradient
in species i.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
It is the concentration gradient
that dictates the rate of ingress.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Gradient in concentration of i in
the x direction.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
Later on, you can generalize this
in three directions.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:30.000
You can replace the derivative with
